==Japanese==
===Noun===
[[馬]][[子]] (まご, mago)

====Sense: Packhorse driver, one who leads horses====
=====Examples=====
# The popular proverb 馬子にも衣装 (mago ni mo issho), literally "even on a packhorse driver, good clothes", meaning "good clothes look good, even on a packhorse driver"
=====Sources======
# [http://www.csse.monash.edu.au/~jwb/edict.html Jim Breen's 'EDICT'] &amp; David Galef's book "Even Monkeys Fall From Trees" list 'Packhorse driver' as an English sense of 馬子.

===Personal name===

[[馬]][[子]] (うまこ, umako)
====Examples====
# 蘇我馬子 (Soga no Umako) (died 626) was a famous leader of the Soga clan. See: [[w:Soga_no_Umako|Wikipedia article on Soga no Umako]]